0	with more than human gifts from heaven adorned 
0	perfections absolute graces divine 
0	and amplitude of mind to greatest deeds 
0	therefore i am returned lest confidence
0	of my success with eve in paradise
0	deceive ye to persuasion over sure
0	of like succeeding here i summon all
0	rather to be in readiness with hand
0	or counsel to assist lest i who erst
0	thought none my equal now be overmatched 
0	so spake the old serpent doubting and from all
0	with clamour was assured their utmost aid
0	at his command when from amidst them rose
0	belial the dissolutest spirit that fell 
0	the sensualest and after asmodai 
0	the fleshliest incubus and thus advised 
0	 set women in his eye and in his walk 
0	among daughters of men the fairest found 
0	many are in each region passing fair
0	as the noon sky more like to goddesses
0	than mortal creatures graceful and discreet 
0	expert in amorous arts enchanting tongues
0	persuasive virgin majesty with mild
0	and sweet allayed yet terrible to approach 
0	skilled to retire and in retiring draw
0	hearts after them tangled in amorous nets 
0	such object hath the power to soften and tame
0	severest temper smooth the rugged st brow 
0	enerve and with voluptuous hope dissolve 
0	draw out with credulous desire and lead
0	at will the manliest resolutest breast 
0	as the magnetic hardest iron draws 
0	women when nothing else beguiled the heart
0	of wisest solomon and made him build 
0	and made him bow to the gods of his wives 
0	to whom quick answer satan thus returned 
0	 belial in much uneven scale thou weigh st
0	all others by thyself because of old
0	thou thyself doat st on womankind admiring
0	their shape their colour and attractive grace 
0	none are thou think st but taken with such toys 
0	before the flood thou with thy lusty crew 
0	false titled sons of god roaming the earth 
0	cast wanton eyes on the daughters of men 
0	and coupled with them and begot a race 
0	have we not seen or by relation heard 
0	in courts and regal chambers how thou lurk st 
0	in wood or grove by mossy fountain side 
0	in valley or green meadow to waylay
0	some beauty rare calisto clymene 
0	or amymone syrinx many more
0	too long then lay st thy scapes on names adored 
0	satyr or faun or silvan but these haunts
0	delight not all among the sons of men
0	how many have with a smile made small account
0	of beauty and her lures easily scorned
0	all her assaults on worthier things intent 
0	remember that pellean conqueror 
0	a youth how all the beauties of the east
0	he slightly viewed and slightly overpassed 
0	how he surnamed of africa dismissed 
0	in his prime youth the fair iberian maid 
0	for solomon he lived at ease and full
0	of honour wealth high fare aimed not beyond
0	higher design than to enjoy his state 
0	thence to the bait of women lay exposed 
0	but he whom we attempt is wiser far
0	than solomon of more exalted mind 
0	made and set wholly on the accomplishment
0	of greatest things what woman will you find 
0	though of this age the wonder and the fame 
0	on whom his leisure will voutsafe an eye
0	of fond desire or should she confident 
0	as sitting queen adored on beauty s throne 
0	descend with all her winning charms begirt
0	to enamour as the zone of venus once
0	wrought that effect on jove so fables tell 
0	how would one look from his majestic brow 
0	seated as on the top of virtue s hill 
0	discountenance her despised and put to rout
0	all her array her female pride deject 
0	or turn to reverent awe for beauty stands
0	in the admiration only of weak minds
0	led captive cease to admire and all her plumes
0	fall flat and shrink into a trivial toy 
0	at every sudden slighting quite abashed 
0	therefore with manlier objects we must try
0	his constancy with such as have more shew
0	of worth of honour glory and popular praise
0	 rocks whereon greatest men have oftest wrecked 
0	or that which only seems to satisfy
0	lawful desires of nature not beyond 
0	and now i know he hungers where no food
0	is to be found in the wide wilderness 
0	the rest commit to me i shall let pass
0	no advantage and his strength as oft assay 
0	he ceased and heard their grant in loud acclaim 
0	then forthwith to him takes a chosen band
0	of spirits likest to himself in guile 
0	to be at hand and at his beck appear 
0	if cause were to unfold some active scene
0	of various persons each to know his part 
0	then to the desert takes with these his flight 
0	where still from shade to shade the son of god 
0	after forty days fasting had remained 
0	now hungering first and to himself thus said 
0	 where will this end four times ten days i have passed
0	wandering this woody maze and human food
0	nor tasted nor had appetite that fast
0	to virtue i impute not or count part
0	of what i suffer here if nature need not 
0	or god support nature without repast 
0	though needing what praise is it to endure 
0	but now i feel i hunger which declares
0	nature hath need of what she asks yet god
0	can satisfy that need some other way 
0	though hunger still remain so it remain
0	without this body s wasting i content me 
0	and from the sting of famine fear no harm 
0	nor mind it fed with better thoughts that feed
0	me hungering more to do my father s will 
0	it was the hour of night when thus the son
0	communed in silent walk then laid him down
0	under the hospitable covert nigh
0	of trees thick interwoven there he slept 
0	and dreamed as appetite is wont to dream 
0	of meats and drinks nature s refreshment sweet 
0	him thought he by the brook of cherith stood 
0	and saw the ravens with their horny beaks
0	food to elijah bringing even and morn 
0	though ravenous taught to abstain from what they brought 
0	he saw the prophet also how he fled
0	into the desert and how there he slept
0	under a juniper then how awaked 
0	he found his supper on the coals prepared 
0	and by the angel was bid rise and eat 
0	and eat the second time after repose 
0	the strength whereof sufficed him forty days 
0	sometimes that with elijah he partook 
0	or as a guest with daniel at his pulse 
0	thus wore out night and now the harald lark
0	left his ground nest high towering to descry
0	the morn s approach and greet her with his song 
0	as lightly from his grassy couch up rose
0	our saviour and found all was but a dream 
0	fasting he went to sleep and fasting waked 
0	up to a hill anon his steps he reared 
0	from whose high top to ken the prospect round 
0	if cottage were in view sheep cote or herd 
0	but cottage herd or sheep cote none he saw 
0	only in a bottom saw a pleasant grove 
0	with chaunt of tuneful birds resounding loud 
0	thither he bent his way determined there
0	to rest at noon and entered soon the shade
0	high roofed and walks beneath and alleys brown 
0	that opened in the midst a woody scene 
0	nature s own work it seemed nature taught art 
0	and to a superstitious eye the haunt
0	of wood gods and wood nymphs he viewed it round 
0	when suddenly a man before him stood 
0	not rustic as before but seemlier clad 
0	as one in city or court or palace bred 
0	and with fair speech these words to him addressed 
0	 with granted leave officious i return 
0	but much more wonder that the son of god
0	in this wild solitude so long should bide 
0	of all things destitute and well i know 
0	not without hunger others of some note 
0	as story tells have trod this wilderness 
0	the fugitive bond woman with her son 
0	outcast nebaioth yet found here relief
0	by a providing angel all the race
0	of israel here had famished had not god
0	rained from heaven manna and that prophet bold 
0	native of thebez wandering here was fed
0	twice by a voice inviting him to eat 
0	of thee those forty days none hath regard 
0	forty and more deserted here indeed 
0	to whom thus jesus what conclud st thou hence 
0	they all had need i as thou seest have none 
0	 how hast thou hunger then satan replied 
0	 tell me if food were now before thee set 
0	wouldst thou not eat thereafter as i like
0	the giver answered jesus why should that
0	cause thy refusal said the subtle fiend 
0	 hast thou not right to all created things 
0	owe not all creatures by just right to thee
0	duty and service nor to stay till bid 
0	but tender all their power nor mention i
0	meats by the law unclean or offered first
0	to idols those young daniel could refuse 
0	nor proffered by an enemy though who
0	would scruple that with want oppressed behold 
0	nature ashamed or better to express 
0	troubled that thou shouldst hunger hath purveyed
0	from all the elements her choicest store 
0	to treat thee as beseems and as her lord
0	with honour only deign to sit and eat 
0	he spake no dream for as his words had end 
0	our saviour lifting up his eyes beheld 
0	in ample space under the broadest shade 
0	a table richly spread in regal mode 
0	with dishes piled and meats of noblest sort
0	and savour beasts of chase or fowl of game 
0	in pastry built or from the spit or boiled 
0	grisamber steamed all fish from sea or shore 
0	freshet or purling brook of shell or fin 
0	and exquisitest name for which was drained
0	pontus and lucrine bay and afric coast 
0	alas how simple to these cates compared 
0	was that crude apple that diverted eve 
0	and at a stately sideboard by the wine 
0	that fragrant smell diffused in order stood
0	tall stripling youths rich clad of fairer hue
0	than ganymed or hylas distant more 
0	under the trees now tripped now solemn stood 
0	nymphs of diana s train and naiades
0	with fruits and flowers from amalthea s horn 
0	and ladies of the hesperides that seemed
0	fairer than feigned of old or fabled since
0	of faery damsels met in forest wide
0	by knights of logres or of lyones 
0	and all the while harmonious airs were heard
0	of chiming strings or charming pipes and winds
0	of gentlest gale arabian odours fanned
0	from their soft wings and flora s earliest smells 
0	such was the splendour and the tempter now
0	his invitation earnestly renewed 
0	 what doubts the son of god to sit and eat 
0	these are not fruits forbidden no interdict
0	defends the touching of these viands pure 
0	their taste no knowledge works at least of evil 
0	but life preserves destroys life s enemy 
0	hunger with sweet restorative delight 
0	all these are spirits of air and woods and springs 
0	thy gentle ministers who come to pay
0	thee homage and acknowledge thee their lord 
0	what doubt st thou son of god sit down and eat 
0	to whom thus jesus temperately replied 
0	 said st thou not that to all things i had right 
0	and who withholds my power that right to use 
0	shall i receive by gift what of my own 
0	when and where likes me best i can command 
0	i can at will doubt not as soon as thou 
0	command a table in this wilderness 
0	and call swift flights of angels ministrant 
0	arrayed in glory on my cup to attend 
0	why shouldst thou then obtrude this diligence
0	in vain where no acceptance it can find 
0	and with my hunger what hast thou to do 
0	thy pompous delicacies i contemn 
0	and count thy specious gifts no gifts but guiles 
0	to whom thus answered satan male content 
0	 that i have also power to give thou seest 
0	if of that power i bring thee voluntary
0	what i might have bestowed on whom i pleased 
0	and rather opportunely in this place
0	chose to impart to thy apparent need 
0	why shouldst thou not accept it but i see
0	what i can do or offer is suspect 
0	of these things others quickly will dispose 
0	whose pains have earned the far fet spoil with that
0	both table and provision vanished quite 
0	with sound of harpies wings and talons heard 
0	only the importune tempter still remained 
0	and with these words his temptation pursued 
0	 by hunger that each other creature tames 
0	thou art not to be harmed therefore not moved 
0	thy temperance invincible besides 
0	for no allurement yields to appetite 
0	and all thy heart is set on high designs 
0	high actions but wherewith to be achieved 
0	great acts require great means of enterprise 
0	thou art unknown unfriended low of birth 
0	a carpenter thy father known thyself
0	bred up in poverty and straits at home 
0	lost in a desert here and hunger bit 
0	which way or from what hope dost thou aspire
0	to greatness whence authority deriv st 
0	what followers what retinue canst thou gain 
0	or at thy heels the dizzy multitude 
0	longer than thou canst feed them on thy cost 
0	money brings honour friends conquest and realms 
0	what raised antipater the edomite 
0	and his son herod placed on juda s throne 
0	thy throne but gold that got him puissant friends 
0	therefore if at great things thou wouldst arrive 
0	get riches first get wealth and treasure heap 
0	not difficult if thou hearken to me 
0	riches are mine fortune is in my hand 
0	they whom i favour thrive in wealth amain 
0	while virtue valour wisdom sit in want 
0	to whom thus jesus patiently replied 
0	 yet wealth without these three is impotent
0	to gain dominion or to keep it gained 
0	witness those ancient empires of the earth 
0	in highth of all their flowing wealth dissolved 
0	but men endued with these have oft attained 
0	in lowest poverty to highest deeds 
0	gideon and jephtha and the shepherd lad
0	whose offspring on the throne of juda sate
0	so many ages and shall yet regain
0	that seat and reign in israel without end 
0	among the heathen for throughout the world
0	to me is not unknown what hath been done
0	worthy of memorial canst thou not remember
0	for i esteem those names of men so poor 
0	who could do mighty things and could contemn
0	riches though offered from the hand of kings 
0	and what in me seems wanting but that i
0	may also in this poverty as soon
0	accomplish what they did perhaps and more 
0	extol not riches then the toil of fools 
0	the wise man s cumbrance if not snare more apt
0	to slacken virtue and abate her edge
0	than prompt her to do aught may merit praise 
0	what if with like aversion i reject
0	riches and realms yet not for that a crown 
0	golden in shew is but a wreath of thorns 
0	brings dangers troubles cares and sleepless nights 
0	to him who wears the regal diadem 
0	when on his shoulders each man s burden lies 
0	for therein stands the office of a king 
0	his honour virtue merit and chief praise 
0	that for the public all this weight he bears 
0	yet he who reigns within himself and rules
0	passions desires and fears is more a king 
0	which every wise and virtuous man attains 
0	and who attains not ill aspires to rule
0	cities of men or headstrong multitudes 
0	subject himself to anarchy within 
0	or lawless passions in him which he serves 
0	but to guide nations in the way of truth
0	by saving doctrine and from error lead
0	to know and knowing worship god aright 
0	is yet more kingly this attracts the soul 
0	governs the inner man the nobler part 
0	that other o er the body only reigns 
0	and oft by force which to a generous mind
0	so reigning can be no sincere delight 
0	besides to give a kingdom hath been thought
0	greater and nobler done and to lay down
0	far more magnanimous than to assume 
0	riches are needless then both for themselves 
0	and for thy reason why they should be sought 
0	to gain a sceptre oftest better missed 
0	so spake the son of god and satan stood
0	a while as mute confounded what to say 
0	what to reply confuted and convinced
0	of his weak arguing and fallacious drift 
0	at length collecting all his serpent wiles 
0	with soothing words renewed him thus accosts 
0	 i see thou know st what is of use to know 
0	what best to say canst say to do canst do 
0	thy actions to thy words accord thy words
0	to thy large heart give utterance due thy heart
0	contains of good wise just the perfet shape 
0	should kings and nations from thy mouth consult 
0	thy counsel would be as the oracle
0	urim and thummim those oraculous gems
0	on aaron s breast or tongue of seers old
0	infallible or wert thou sought to deeds
0	that might require the array of war thy skill
0	of conduct would be such that all the world
0	could not sustain thy prowess or subsist
0	in battle though against thy few in arms 
0	these godlike virtues wherefore dost thou hide 
0	affecting private life or more obscure
0	in savage wilderness wherefore deprive
0	all earth her wonder at thy acts thyself
0	the fame and glory glory the reward
0	that sole excites to high attempts the flame
0	of most erected spirits most tempered pure
0	aethereal who all pleasures else despise 
0	all treasures and all gain esteem as dross 
0	and dignities and powers all but the highest 
0	thy years are ripe and over ripe the son
0	of macedonian philip had ere these
0	won asia and the throne of cyrus held
0	at his dispose young scipio had brought down
0	the carthaginian pride young pompey quelled
0	the pontic king and in triumph had rode 
0	yet years and to ripe years judgment mature 
0	quench not the thirst of glory but augment 
0	great julius whom now all the world admires 
0	the more he grew in years the more inflamed
0	with glory wept that he had lived so long
0	ingloroious but thou yet art not too late 
0	to whom our saviour calmly thus replied 
0	 thou neither dost persuade me to seek wealth
0	for empire s sake nor empire to affect
0	for glory s sake by all thy argument 
0	for what is glory but the blaze of fame 
0	the people s praise if always praise unmixed 
0	and what the people but a herd confused 
0	a miscellaneous rabble who extol
0	things vulgar and well weighed scarce worth the praise 
0	they praise and they admire they know not what 
0	and know not whom but as one leads the other 
0	and what delight to be by such extolled 
0	to live upon their tongues and be their talk 
0	of whom to be dispraised were no small praise 
0	his lot who dares be singularly good 
0	the intelligent among them and the wise
0	are few and glory scarce of few is raised 
0	this is true glory and renown when god 
0	looking on the earth with approbation marks
0	the just man and divulges him through heaven
0	to all his angels who with true applause
0	recount his praises thus he did to job 
0	when to extend his fame through heaven and earth 
0	as thou to thy reproach may st well remember 
0	he asked thee hast thou seen my servant job 
0	famous he was in heaven on earth less known 
0	where glory is false glory attributed
0	to things not glorious men not worthy of fame 
0	they err who count it glorious to subdue
0	by conquest far and wide to overrun
0	large countries and in field great battles win 
0	great cities by assault what do these worthies
0	but rob and spoil burn slaughter and enslave
0	peaceable nations neighbouring or remote 
0	made captive yet deserving freedom more
0	than those their conquerors who leave behind
0	nothing but ruin wheresoe er they rove 
0	and all the flourishing works of peace destroy 
0	then swell with pride and must be titled gods 
0	great benefactors of mankind deliverers 
0	worshipped with temple priest and sacrifice 
0	one is the son of jove of mars the other 
0	till conqueror death discover them scarce men 
0	rowling in brutish vices and deformed 
0	violent or shameful death their due reward 
0	but if there be in glory aught of good 
0	it may be means far different be attained 
0	without ambition war or violence 
0	by deeds of peace by wisdom eminent 
0	by patience temperance i mention still
0	him whom thy wrongs with saintly patience borne 
0	made famous in a land and times obscure 
0	who names not now with honour patient job 
0	poor socrates who next more memorable 
0	by what he taught and suffered for so doing 
0	for truth s sake suffering death unjust lives now
0	equal in fame to proudest conquerors 
0	yet if for fame and glory aught be done 
0	aught suffered if young african for fame
0	his wasted country freed from punic rage 
0	the deed becomes unpraised the man at least 
0	and loses though but verbal his reward 
0	shall i seek glory then as vain men seek 
0	oft not deserved i seek not mine but his
0	who sent me and thereby witness whence i am 
0	to whom the tempter murmuring thus replied 
0	 think not so slight of glory therein least
0	resembling thy great father he seeks glory 
0	and for his glory all things made all things
0	orders and governs nor content in heaven 
0	by all his angels glorified requires
0	glory from men from all men good or bad 
0	wise or unwise no difference no exemption 
0	above all sacrifice or hallowed gift 
0	glory he requires and glory he receives 
0	or barbarous nor exception hath declared 
0	from us his foes pronounced glory he exacts 
0	to whom our saviour fervently replied 
0	 and reason since his word all things produced 
0	though chiefly not for glory as prime end 
0	but to shew forth his goodness and impart
0	his good communicable to every soul
0	freely of whom what could he less expect
0	than glory and benediction that is thanks 
0	the slightest easiest readiest recompense
0	from them who could return him nothing else 
0	and not returning that would likeliest render
0	contempt instead dishonour obloquy 
0	hard recompense unsuitable return
0	for so much good so much beneficience 
0	but why should man seek glory who of his own
0	hath nothing and to whom nothing belongs
0	but condemnation ignominy and shame 
0	who for so many benefits received 
0	turned recreant to god ingrate and false 
0	and so of all true good himself despoiled 
0	yet sacrilegious to himself would take
0	that which to god alone of right belongs 
0	yet so much bounty is in god such grace 
0	that who advances his glory not their own 
0	them he himself to glory will advance 
0	so spake the son of god and here again
0	satan had not to answer but stood struck
0	with guilt of his own sin for he himself 
0	insatiable of glory had lost all 
0	yet of another plea bethought him soon 
0	 of glory as thou wilt said he so deem 
0	worth or not worth the seeking let it pass 
0	but to a kingdom thou art born ordained
0	to sit upon thy father david s throne 
0	by mother s side thy father though thy right
0	be now in powerful hands that will not part
0	easily from possession won with arms 
0	reduced a province under roman yoke 
0	obeys tiberius nor is always ruled
0	with temperate sway oft have they violated
