0	thy politic maxims or that cumbersome
0	luggage of war there shewn me argument
0	of human weakness rather than of strength 
0	my brethren as thou call st them those ten tribes 
0	i must deliver if i mean to reign
0	david s true heir and his full sceptre sway
0	to just extent over all israel s sons 
0	but whence to thee this zeal where was it then
0	for israel or for david or his throne 
0	when thou stood st up his tempter to the pride
0	of numbering israel which cost the lives
0	of threescore and ten thousand israelites
0	by three days pestilence such was thy zeal
0	to israel then the same that now to me 
0	as for those captive tribes themselves were they
0	who wrought their own captivity fell off
0	from god to worship calves the deities
0	and all the idolatries of heathen round 
0	besides their other worse than heathenish crimes 
0	nor in the land of their captivity
0	humbled themselves or penitent besought
0	the god of their forefathers but so died
0	impenitent and left a race behind
0	like to themselves distinguishable scarce
0	from gentiles but by circumcision vain 
0	and god with idols in their worship joined 
0	should i of these the liberty regard 
0	who freed as to their ancient patrimony 
0	unhumbled unrepentant unreformed 
0	headlong would follow and to their gods perhaps
0	of bethel and of dan no let them serve
0	their enemies who serve idols with god 
0	yet he at length time to himself best known 
0	remembering abraham by some wondrous call
0	may bring them back repentant and sincere 
0	and at their passing cleave the assyrian flood 
0	while to their native land with joy they haste 
0	as the red sea and jordan once he cleft 
0	when to the promised land their fathers passed 
0	to his due time and providence i leave them 
0	so spake israel s true king and to the fiend
0	made answer meet that made void all his wiles 
0	so fares it when with truth falsehood contends 
0	perplexed and troubled at his bad success
0	the tempter stood nor had what to reply 
0	discovered in his fraud thrown from his hope
0	so oft and the persuasive rhetoric
0	that sleeked his tongue and won so much on eve 
0	so little here nay lost but eve was eve 
0	this far his over match who self deceived
0	and rash beforehand had no better weighed
0	the strength he was to cope with or his own 
0	but as a man who had been matchless held
0	in cunning over reached where least he thought 
0	to salve his credit and for very spite 
0	still will be tempting him who foils him still 
0	and never cease though to his shame the more 
0	or as a swarm of flies in vintage time 
0	about the wine press where sweet must is poured 
0	beat off returns as oft with humming sound 
0	or surging waves against a solid rock 
0	though all to shivers dashed the assault renew 
0	 vain battery and in froth or bubbles end 
0	so satan whom repulse upon repulse
0	met ever and to shameful silence brought 
0	yet gives not o er though desperate of success 
0	and his vain importunity pursues 
0	he brought our saviour to the western side
0	of that high mountain whence he might behold
0	another plain long but in breadth not wide 
0	washed by the southern sea and on the north
0	to equal length backed with a ridge of hills
0	that screened the fruits of the earth and seats of men
0	from cold septentrion blasts thence in the midst
0	divided by a river off whose banks
0	on each side an imperial city stood 
0	with towers and temples proudly elevate
0	on seven small hills with palaces adorned 
0	porches and theatres baths aqueducts 
0	statues and trophies and triumphal arcs 
0	gardens and groves presented to his eyes
0	above the highth of mountains interposed 
0	by what strange parallax or optic skill
0	of vision multiplied through air or glass
0	of telescope were curious to enquire 
0	and now the tempter thus his silence broke 
0	 the city which thou seest no other deem
0	than great and glorious rome queen of the earth
0	so far renowned and with the spoils enriched
0	of nations there the capitol thou seest 
0	above the rest lifting his stately head
0	on the tarpeian rock her citadel
0	impregnable and there mount palatine 
0	the imperial palace compass huge and high
0	the structure skill of noblest architects 
0	with gilded battlements conspicuous far 
0	turrets and terraces and glittering spires 
0	many a fair edifice besides more like
0	houses of gods so well i have disposed
0	my aerie microscope thou may st behold 
0	outside and inside both pillars and roofs
0	carved work the hand of famed artificers
0	in cedar marble ivory or gold 
0	thence to the gates cast round thine eye and see
0	what conflux issuing forth or entering in 
0	praetors proconsuls to their provinces
0	hasting or on return in robes of state 
0	lictors and rods the ensigns of their power 
0	legions and cohorts turms of horse and wings 
0	or embassies from regions far remote 
0	in various habits on the appian road 
0	or on the aemilian some from farthest south 
0	syene and where the shadow both way falls 
0	meroe nilotic isle and more to west 
0	the realm of bocchus to the blackmoor sea 
0	from the asian kings and parthian among these 
0	and utmost indian isle taprobane 
0	dusk faces with white silken turbants wreathed 
0	from gallia gades and the british west 
0	germans and scythians and sarmatians north
0	beyond danubius to the tauric pool 
0	all nations now to rome obedience pay 
0	to rome s great emperor whose wide domain 
0	in ample territory wealth and power 
0	civility of manners arts and arms 
0	and long renown thou justly may st prefer
0	before the parthian these two thrones except 
0	the rest are barbarous and scarce worth the sight 
0	shared among petty kings too far removed 
0	these having shewn thee i have shewn thee all
0	the kingdoms of the world and all their glory 
0	this emperor hath no son and now is old 
0	old and lascivious and from rome retired
0	to capreae an island small but strong
0	on the campanian shore with purpose there
0	his horrid lusts in private to enjoy 
0	committing to a wicked favourite
0	all public cares and yet of him suspicious 
0	hated of all and hating with what ease 
0	endued with regal virtues as thou art 
0	appearing and beginning noble deeds 
0	might st thou expel this monster from his throne 
0	now made a sty and in his place ascending 
0	a victor people free from servile yoke 
0	and with my help thou may st to me the power
0	is given and by that right i give it thee 
0	aim therefore at no less than all the world 
0	aim at the highest without the highest attained 
0	will be for thee no sitting or not long 
0	on david s throne be prophesied what will 
0	to whom the son of god unmoved replied 
0	 nor doth this grandeur and majestic shew
0	of luxury though called magnificence 
0	more than of arms before allure mine eye 
0	much less my mind though thou should st add to tell
0	their sumptuous gluttonies and gorgeous feasts
0	on citron tables or atlantic stone
0	 for i have also heard perhaps have read 
0	their wines of setia cales and falerne 
0	chios and crete and how they quaff in gold 
0	crystal and myrrhine cups imbossed with gems
0	and studs of pearl to me should st tell who thirst
0	and hunger still then embassies thou shew st
0	from nations far and nigh what honour that 
0	but tedious waste of time to sit and hear
0	so many hollow compliments and lies 
0	outlandish flatteries then proceed st to talk
0	of the emperor how easily subdued 
0	how gloriously i shall thou say st expel
0	a brutish monster what if i withal
0	expel a devil who first made him such 
0	let his tormentor conscience find him out 
0	for him i was not sent nor yet to free
0	that people victor once now vile and base 
0	deservedly made vassal who once just 
0	frugal and mild and temperate conquered well 
0	but govern ill the nations under yoke 
0	peeling their provinces exhausted all
0	by lust and rapine first ambitious grown
0	of triumph that insulting vanity 
0	then cruel by their sports to blood inured
0	of fighting beasts and men to beasts exposed 
0	luxurious by their wealth and greedier still 
0	and from the daily scene effeminate 
0	what wise and valiant man would seek to free
0	these thus degenerate by themselves enslaved 
0	or could of inward slaves make outward free 
0	know therefore when my season comes to sit
0	on david s throne it shall be like a tree
0	spreading and overshadowing all the earth 
0	or as a stone that shall to pieces dash
0	all monarchies besides throughout the world 
0	and of my kingdom there shall be no end 
0	means there shall be to this but what the means
0	is not for thee to know nor me to tell 
0	to whom the tempter impudent replied 
0	 i see all offers made by me how slight
0	thou valuest because offered and reject st 
0	nothing will please the difficult and nice 
0	or nothing more than still to contradict 
0	on the other side know also thou that i
0	on what i offer set as high esteem 
0	nor what i part with mean to give for naught 
0	all these which in a moment thou behold st 
0	the kingdoms of the world to thee i give
0	 for given to me i give to whom i please 
0	no trifle yet with this reserve not else 
0	on this condition if thou wilt fall down 
0	and worship me as thy superior lord
0	 easily done and hold them all of me 
0	for what can less so great a gift deserve 
0	whom thus our saviour answered with disdain 
0	 i never liked thy talk thy offers less 
0	now both abhor since thou hast dared to utter
0	the abominable terms impious condition 
0	but i endure the time till which expired
0	thou hast permission on me it is written 
0	the first of all commandments thou shalt worship
0	the lord thy god and only him shalt serve 
0	and dar st thou to the son of god propound
0	to worship thee accursed now more accursed
0	for this attempt bolder than that on eve 
0	and more blasphemous which expect to rue 
0	the kingdoms of the world to thee were given 
0	permitted rather and by thee usurped 
0	other donation none thou canst produce 
0	if given by whom but by the king of kings 
0	god over all supreme if given to thee 
0	by thee how fairly is the giver now
0	repaid but gratitude in thee is lost
0	long since wert thou so void of fear or shame
0	as offer them to me the son of god 
0	to me my own on such abhorred pact 
0	that i fall down and worship thee as god 
0	get thee behind me plain thou now appear st
0	that evil one satan for ever damned 
0	to whom the fiend with fear abashed replied 
0	 be not so sore offended son of god 
0	though sons of god both angels are and men 
0	if i to try whether in higher sort
0	than these thou bear st that title have proposed
0	what both from men and angels i receive 
0	nations besides from all the quartered winds 
0	god of this world invoked and world beneath 
0	who then thou art whose coming is foretold
0	to me most fatal me it most concerns 
0	the trial hath indamaged thee no way 
0	rather more honour left and more esteem 
0	me naught advantaged missing what i aimed 
0	therefore let pass as they are transitory 
0	the kingdoms of this world i shall no more
0	advise thee gain them as thou canst or not 
0	and thou thyself seem st otherwise inclined
0	than to a worldly crown addicted more
0	to contemplation and profound dispute 
0	as by that early action may be judged 
0	when slipping from thy mother s eye thou went st
0	alone into the temple there wast found
0	among the gravest rabbies disputant
0	on points and questions fitting moses chair 
0	teaching not taught the childhood shews the man 
0	as morning shews the day be famous then 
0	by wisdom as thy empire must extend 
0	so let extend thy mind o er all the world
0	in knowledge all things in it comprehend 
0	all knowledge is not couched in moses law 
0	the pentateuch or what the prophets wrote 
0	the gentiles also know and write and teach
0	to admiration led by nature s light 
0	and with the gentiles much thou must converse 
0	ruling them by persuasion as thou mean st 
0	without their learning how wilt thou with them 
0	or they with thee hold conversation meet 
0	how wilt thou reason with them how refute
0	their idolisms traditions paradoxes 
0	error by his own arms is best evinced 
0	look once more ere we leave this specular mount 
0	westward much nearer by south west behold
0	where on the aegean shore a city stands 
0	built nobly pure the air and light the soil 
0	athens the eye of greece mother of arts
0	and eloquence native to famous wits
0	or hospitable in her sweet recess 
0	city or suburban studious walks and shades 
0	see there the olive grove of academe 
0	plato s retirement where the attic bird
0	trills her thick warbled notes the summer long 
0	there flowery hill hymettus with the sound
0	of bees industrious murmur oft invites
0	to studious musing there ilissus rowls
0	his whispering stream within the walls then view
0	the schools of ancient sages his who bred
0	great alexander to subdue the world 
0	there thou shalt hear and learn the secret power
0	of harmony in tones and numbers hit
0	by voice or hand and various measured verse 
0	aeolian charms and dorian lyric odes 
0	and his who gave them breath but higher sung 
0	blind melesigenes thence homer called 
0	whose poem phoebus challenged for his own 
0	thence what the lofty grave tragedians taught
0	in chorus or iambic teachers best
0	of moral prudence with delight received
0	in brief sententious precepts while they treat
0	of fate and chance and change in human life 
0	high actions and high passions best describing 
0	thence to the famous orators repair 
0	those ancient whose resistless eloquence
0	wielded at will that fierce democraty 
0	shook the arsenal and fulmined over greece
0	to macedon and artaxerxes throne 
0	to sage philosophy next lend thine ear 
0	from heaven descended to the low roofed house
0	of socrates see there his tenement 
0	whom well inspired the oracle pronounced
0	wisest of men from whose mouth issued forth
0	mellifluous streams that watered all the schools
0	of academics old and new with those
0	surnamed peripatetics and the sect
0	epicurean and the stoic severe 
0	these here revolve or as thou likest at home 
0	till time mature thee to a kingdom s weight 
0	these rules will render thee a king complete
0	within thyself much more with empire joined 
0	to whom our saviour sagely thus replied 
0	 think not but that i know these things or think
0	i know them not not therefore am i short
0	of knowing what i ought he who receives
0	light from above from the fountain of light 
0	no other doctrine needs though granted true 
0	but these are false or little else but dreams 
0	conjectures fancies built on nothing firm 
0	the first and wisest of them all professed
0	to know this only that he nothing knew 
0	the next to fabling fell and smooth conceits 
0	a third sort doubted all things though plain sense 
0	others in virtue placed felicity 
0	but virtue joined with riches and long life 
0	in corporal pleasure he and careless ease 
0	the stoic last in philosophic pride 
0	by him called virtue and his virtuous man 
0	wise perfect in himself and all possessing 
0	equal to god oft shames not to prefer 
0	as fearing god nor man contemning all
0	wealth pleasure pain or torment death and life 
0	which when he lists he leaves or boasts he can 
0	for all his tedious talk is but vain boast 
0	or subtle shifts conviction to evade 
0	alas what can they teach and not mislead 
0	ignorant of themselves of god much more 
0	and how the world began and how man fell 
0	degraded by himself on grace depending 
0	much of the soul they talk but all awry 
0	and in themselves seek virtue and to themselves
0	all glory arrogate to god give none 
0	rather accuse him under usual names 
0	fortune and fate as one regardless quite
0	of mortal things who therefore seeks in these
0	true wisdom finds her not or by delusion
0	far worse her false resemblance only meets 
0	an empty cloud however many books 
0	wise men have said are wearisome who reads
0	incessantly and to his reading brings not
0	a spirit and judgment equal or superior 
0	 and what he brings what needs he elsewhere seek 
0	uncertain and unsettled still remains 
0	deep versed in books and shallow in himself 
0	crude or intoxicate collecting toys
0	and trifles for choice matters worth a sponge 
0	as children gathering pebbles on the shore 
0	or if i would delight my private hours
0	with music or with poem where so soon
0	as in our native language can i find
0	that solace all our law and story strewed
0	with hymns our psalms with artful terms inscribed 
0	our hebrew songs and harps in babylon
0	that pleased so well our victor s ear declare
0	that rather greece from us these arts derived 
0	ill imitated while they loudest sing
0	the vices of their deities and their own 
0	in fable hymn or song so personating
0	their gods ridiculous and themselves past shame 
0	remove their swelling epithetes thick laid
0	as varnish on a harlot s cheek the rest 
0	thin sown with aught of profit or delight 
0	will far be found unworthy to compare
0	with sion s songs to all true tastes excelling 
0	where god is praised aright and godlike men 
0	 such are from god inspired not such from thee 
0	unless where moral virtue is expressed
0	by light of nature not in all quite lost 
0	their orators thou then extoll st as those
0	the top of eloquence statists indeed 
0	and lovers of their country as may seem 
0	but herein to our prophets far beneath 
0	as men divinely taught and better teaching
0	the solid rules of civil government 
0	in their majestic unaffected style 
0	than all the oratory of greece and rome 
0	in them is plainest taught and easiest learnt 
0	what makes a nation happy and keeps it so 
0	what ruins kingdoms and lays cities flat 
0	these only with our law best form a king 
0	so spake the son of god but satan now
0	quite at a loss for all his darts were spent 
0	thus to our saviour with stern brow replied 
0	 since neither wealth nor honour arms nor arts 
0	kingdom nor empire pleases thee nor aught
0	by me proposed in life contemplative
0	or active tended on by glory or fame 
0	what dost thou in this world the wilderness
0	for thee is fittest place i found thee there 
0	and thither will return thee yet remember
0	what i foretell thee soon thou shalt have cause
0	to wish thou never hadst rejected thus
0	nicely or cautiously my offered aid 
0	which would have set thee in short time with ease
0	on david s throne or throne of all the world 
0	now at full age fulness of time thy season 
0	when prophecies of thee are best fulfilled 
0	now contrary if i read aught in heaven 
0	or heaven write aught of fate by what the stars
0	voluminous or single characters
0	in their conjunction met give me to spell 
0	sorrows and labours opposition hate 
0	attends thee scorns reproaches injuries 
0	violence and stripes and lastly cruel death 
0	a kingdom they portend thee but what kingdom 
0	real or allegoric i discern not 
0	nor when eternal sure as without end 
0	without beginning for no date prefixed
0	directs me in the starry rubric set 
0	so saying he took for still he knew his power
0	not yet expired and to the wilderness
0	brought back the son of god and left him there 
0	feigning to disappear darkness now rose 
0	as daylight sunk and brought in louring night 
0	her shadowy offspring unsubstantial both 
0	privation mere of light and absent day 
0	our saviour meek and with untroubled mind
0	after hisaerie jaunt though hurried sore 
0	hungry and cold betook him to his rest 
0	wherever under some concourse of shades 
0	whose branching arms thick intertwined might shield
0	from dews and damps of night his sheltered head 
0	but sheltered slept in vain for at his head
0	the tempter watched and soon with ugly dreams
0	disturbed his sleep and either tropic now
0	 gan thunder and both ends of heaven the clouds
0	from many a horrid rift abortive poured
0	fierce rain with lightning mixed water with fire 
0	in ruin reconciled nor slept the winds
0	within their stony caves but rushed abroad
0	from the four hinges of the world and fell
0	on the vexed wilderness whose tallest pines 
0	though rooted deep as high and sturdiest oaks 
0	bowed their stiff necks loaden with stormy blasts 
0	or torn up sheer ill wast thou shrouded then 
0	o patient son of god yet only stood st
0	unshaken nor yet staid the terror there 
0	infernal ghosts and hellish furies round
0	environed thee some howled some yelled some shrieked 
0	some bent at thee their fiery darts while thou
0	sat st unappalled in calm and sinless peace 
0	thus passed the night so foul till morning fair
0	came forth with pilgrim steps in amice grey 
0	who with her radiant finger stilled the roar
0	of thunder chased the clouds and laid the winds 
0	and griesly spectres which the fiend had raised
0	to tempt the son of god with terrors dire 
0	and now the sun with more effectual beams
0	had cheered the face of earth and dried the wet
0	from drooping plant or dropping tree the birds 
0	who all things now behold more fresh and green 
0	after a night of storm so ruinous 
0	cleared up their choicest notes in bush and spray 
0	to gratulate the sweet return of morn 
0	nor yet amidst this joy and brightest morn 
0	was absent after all his mischief done 
0	the prince of darkness glad would also seem
0	of this fair change and to our saviour came 
0	yet with no new device they all were spent 
0	rather by this his last affront resolved 
0	desperate of better course to vent his rage
0	and mad despite to be so oft repelled 
0	him walking on a sunny hill he found 
0	backed on the north and west by a thick wood 
0	out of the wood he starts in wonted shape 
0	and in a careless mood thus to him said 
0	 fair morning yet betides thee son of god 
0	after a dismal night i heard the wrack 
0	as earth and sky would mingle but myself
0	was distant and these flaws though mortals fear them 
0	as dangerous to the pillared frame of heaven 
0	or to the earth s dark basis underneath 
0	are to the main as inconsiderable
0	and harmless if not wholesome as a sneeze
0	to man s less universe and soon are gone 
0	yet as being ofttimes noxious where they light
0	on man beast plant wasteful and turbulent 
0	like turbulencies in the affairs of men 
0	over whose heads they roar and seem to point 
0	they oft fore signify and threaten ill 
0	this tempest at this desert most was bent 
0	of men at thee for only thou here dwell st 
0	did i not tell thee if thou didst reject
0	the perfect season offered with my aid
0	to win thy destined seat but wilt prolong
0	all to the push of fate pursue thy way
0	of gaining david s throne no man knows when
0	 for both the when and how is nowhere told 
0	thou shalt be what thou art ordained no doubt 
0	for angels have proclaimed it but concealing
0	the time and means each act is rightliest done
0	not when it must but when it may be best 
0	if thou observe not this be sure to find
0	what i foretold thee many a hard assay
0	of dangers and adversities and pains 
0	ere thou of israel s sceptre get fast hold 
0	whereof this ominous night that closed thee round 
0	so many terrors voices prodigies 
0	may warn thee as a sure foregoing sign 
0	so talked he while the son of god went on 
