0	not unattended for on her as queen 
0	a pomp of winning graces waited still 
0	and from about her shot darts of desire
0	into all eyes to wish her still in sight 
0	and raphael now to adam s doubt proposed 
0	benevolent and facile thus replied 
0	to ask or search i blame thee not for heaven
0	is as the book of god before thee set 
0	wherein to read his wonderous works and learn
0	his seasons hours or days or months or years 
0	this to attain whether heaven move or earth 
0	imports not if thou reckon right the rest
0	from man or angel the great architect
0	did wisely to conceal and not divulge
0	his secrets to be scanned by them who ought
0	rather admire or if they list to try
0	conjecture he his fabrick of the heavens
0	hath left to their disputes perhaps to move
0	his laughter at their quaint opinions wide
0	hereafter when they come to model heaven
0	and calculate the stars how they will wield
0	the mighty frame how build unbuild contrive
0	to save appearances how gird the sphere
0	with centrick and eccentrick scribbled o er 
0	cycle and epicycle orb in orb 
0	already by thy reasoning this i guess 
0	who art to lead thy offspring and supposest
0	that bodies bright and greater should not serve
0	the less not bright nor heaven such journeys run 
0	earth sitting still when she alone receives
0	the benefit consider first that great
0	or bright infers not excellence the earth
0	though in comparison of heaven so small 
0	nor glistering may of solid good contain
0	more plenty than the sun that barren shines 
0	whose virtue on itself works no effect 
0	but in the fruitful earth there first received 
0	his beams unactive else their vigour find 
0	yet not to earth are those bright luminaries
0	officious but to thee earth s habitant 
0	and for the heaven s wide circuit let it speak
0	the maker s high magnificence who built
0	so spacious and his line stretched out so far 
0	that man may know he dwells not in his own 
0	an edifice too large for him to fill 
0	lodged in a small partition and the rest
0	ordained for uses to his lord best known 
0	the swiftness of those circles attribute 
0	though numberless to his omnipotence 
0	that to corporeal substances could add
0	speed almost spiritual me thou thinkest not slow 
0	who since the morning hour set out from heaven
0	where god resides and ere mid day arrived
0	in eden distance inexpressible
0	by numbers that have name but this i urge 
0	admitting motion in the heavens to show
0	invalid that which thee to doubt it moved 
0	not that i so affirm though so it seem
0	to thee who hast thy dwelling here on earth 
0	god to remove his ways from human sense 
0	placed heaven from earth so far that earthly sight 
0	if it presume might err in things too high 
0	and no advantage gain what if the sun
0	be center to the world and other stars 
0	by his attractive virtue and their own
0	incited dance about him various rounds 
0	their wandering course now high now low then hid 
0	progressive retrograde or standing still 
0	in six thou seest and what if seventh to these
0	the planet earth so stedfast though she seem 
0	insensibly three different motions move 
0	which else to several spheres thou must ascribe 
0	moved contrary with thwart obliquities 
0	or save the sun his labour and that swift
0	nocturnal and diurnal rhomb supposed 
0	invisible else above all stars the wheel
0	of day and night which needs not thy belief 
0	if earth industrious of herself fetch day
0	travelling east and with her part averse
0	from the sun s beam meet night her other part
0	still luminous by his ray what if that light 
0	sent from her through the wide transpicuous air 
0	to the terrestrial moon be as a star 
0	enlightening her by day as she by night
0	this earth reciprocal if land be there 
0	fields and inhabitants her spots thou seest
0	as clouds and clouds may rain and rain produce
0	fruits in her softened soil for some to eat
0	allotted there and other suns perhaps 
0	with their attendant moons thou wilt descry 
0	communicating male and female light 
0	which two great sexes animate the world 
0	stored in each orb perhaps with some that live 
0	for such vast room in nature unpossessed
0	by living soul desart and desolate 
0	only to shine yet scarce to contribute
0	each orb a glimpse of light conveyed so far
0	down to this habitable which returns
0	light back to them is obvious to dispute 
0	but whether thus these things or whether not 
0	but whether the sun predominant in heaven 
0	rise on the earth or earth rise on the sun 
0	he from the east his flaming road begin 
0	or she from west her silent course advance 
0	with inoffensive pace that spinning sleeps
0	on her soft axle while she paces even 
0	and bears thee soft with the smooth hair along 
0	sollicit not thy thoughts with matters hid 
0	leave them to god above him serve and fear 
0	of other creatures as him pleases best 
0	wherever placed let him dispose joy thou
0	in what he gives to thee this paradise
0	and thy fair eve heaven is for thee too high
0	to know what passes there be lowly wise 
0	think only what concerns thee and thy being 
0	dream not of other worlds what creatures there
0	live in what state condition or degree 
0	contented that thus far hath been revealed
0	not of earth only but of highest heaven 
0	to whom thus adam cleared of doubt replied 
0	how fully hast thou satisfied me pure
0	intelligence of heaven angel serene 
0	and freed from intricacies taught to live
0	the easiest way nor with perplexing thoughts
0	to interrupt the sweet of life from which
0	god hath bid dwell far off all anxious cares 
0	and not molest us unless we ourselves
0	seek them with wandering thoughts and notions vain 
0	but apt the mind or fancy is to rove
0	unchecked and of her roving is no end 
0	till warned or by experience taught she learn 
0	that not to know at large of things remote
0	from use obscure and subtle but to know
0	that which before us lies in daily life 
0	is the prime wisdom what is more is fume 
0	or emptiness or fond impertinence 
0	and renders us in things that most concern 
0	unpractised unprepared and still to seek 
0	therefore from this high pitch let us descend
0	a lower flight and speak of things at hand
0	useful whence haply mention may arise
0	of something not unseasonable to ask 
0	by sufferance and thy wonted favour deigned 
0	thee i have heard relating what was done
0	ere my remembrance now hear me relate
0	my story which perhaps thou hast not heard 
0	and day is not yet spent till then thou seest
0	how subtly to detain thee i devise 
0	inviting thee to hear while i relate 
0	fond were it not in hope of thy reply 
0	for while i sit with thee i seem in heaven 
0	and sweeter thy discourse is to my ear
0	than fruits of palm tree pleasantest to thirst
0	and hunger both from labour at the hour
0	of sweet repast they satiate and soon fill 
0	though pleasant but thy words with grace divine
0	imbued bring to their sweetness no satiety 
0	to whom thus raphael answered heavenly meek 
0	nor are thy lips ungraceful sire of men 
0	nor tongue ineloquent for god on thee
0	abundantly his gifts hath also poured
0	inward and outward both his image fair 
0	speaking or mute all comeliness and grace
0	attends thee and each word each motion forms 
0	nor less think we in heaven of thee on earth
0	than of our fellow servant and inquire
0	gladly into the ways of god with man 
0	for god we see hath honoured thee and set
0	on man his equal love say therefore on 
0	for i that day was absent as befel 
0	bound on a voyage uncouth and obscure 
0	far on excursion toward the gates of hell 
0	squared in full legion such command we had 
0	to see that none thence issued forth a spy 
0	or enemy while god was in his work 
0	lest he incensed at such eruption bold 
0	destruction with creation might have mixed 
0	not that they durst without his leave attempt 
0	but us he sends upon his high behests
0	for state as sovran king and to inure
0	our prompt obedience fast we found fast shut 
0	the dismal gates and barricadoed strong 
0	but long ere our approaching heard within
0	noise other than the sound of dance or song 
0	torment and loud lament and furious rage 
0	glad we returned up to the coasts of light
0	ere sabbath evening so we had in charge 
0	but thy relation now for i attend 
0	pleased with thy words no less than thou with mine 
0	so spake the godlike power and thus our sire 
0	for man to tell how human life began
0	is hard for who himself beginning knew
0	desire with thee still longer to converse
0	induced me as new waked from soundest sleep 
0	soft on the flowery herb i found me laid 
0	in balmy sweat which with his beams the sun
0	soon dried and on the reeking moisture fed 
0	straight toward heaven my wondering eyes i turned 
0	and gazed a while the ample sky till raised
0	by quick instinctive motion up i sprung 
0	as thitherward endeavouring and upright
0	stood on my feet about me round i saw
0	hill dale and shady woods and sunny plains 
0	and liquid lapse of murmuring streams by these 
0	creatures that lived and moved and walked or flew 
0	birds on the branches warbling all things smiled 
0	with fragrance and with joy my heart o erflowed 
0	myself i then perused and limb by limb
0	surveyed and sometimes went and sometimes ran
0	with supple joints as lively vigour led 
0	but who i was or where or from what cause 
0	knew not to speak i tried and forthwith spake 
0	my tongue obeyed and readily could name
0	whate er i saw thou sun said i fair light 
0	and thou enlightened earth so fresh and gay 
0	and ye that live and move fair creatures tell 
0	tell if ye saw how i came thus how here 
0	not of myself by some great maker then 
0	in goodness and in power pre eminent 
0	tell me how may i know him how adore 
0	from whom i have that thus i move and live 
0	and feel that i am happier than i know 
0	while thus i called and strayed i knew not whither 
0	from where i first drew air and first beheld
0	this happy light when answer none returned 
0	on a green shady bank profuse of flowers 
0	pensive i sat me down there gentle sleep
0	first found me and with soft oppression seised
0	my droused sense untroubled though i thought
0	i then was passing to my former state
0	insensible and forthwith to dissolve 
0	when suddenly stood at my head a dream 
0	whose inward apparition gently moved
0	my fancy to believe i yet had being 
0	and lived one came methought of shape divine 
0	and said thy mansion wants thee adam rise 
0	first man of men innumerable ordained
0	first father called by thee i come thy guide
0	to the garden of bliss thy seat prepared 
0	so saying by the hand he took me raised 
0	and over fields and waters as in air
0	smooth sliding without step last led me up
0	a woody mountain whose high top was plain 
0	a circuit wide enclosed with goodliest trees
0	planted with walks and bowers that what i saw
0	of earth before scarce pleasant seemed each tree 
0	loaden with fairest fruit that hung to the eye
0	tempting stirred in me sudden appetite
0	to pluck and eat whereat i waked and found
0	before mine eyes all real as the dream
0	had lively shadowed here had new begun
0	my wandering had not he who was my guide
0	up hither from among the trees appeared 
0	presence divine rejoicing but with awe 
0	in adoration at his feet i fell
0	submiss he reared me and whom thou soughtest i am 
0	said mildly author of all this thou seest
0	above or round about thee or beneath 
0	this paradise i give thee count it thine
0	to till and keep and of the fruit to eat 
0	of every tree that in the garden grows
0	eat freely with glad heart fear here no dearth 
0	but of the tree whose operation brings
0	knowledge of good and ill which i have set
0	the pledge of thy obedience and thy faith 
0	amid the garden by the tree of life 
0	remember what i warn thee shun to taste 
0	and shun the bitter consequence for know 
0	the day thou eatest thereof my sole command
0	transgressed inevitably thou shalt die 
0	from that day mortal and this happy state
0	shalt lose expelled from hence into a world
0	of woe and sorrow sternly he pronounced
0	the rigid interdiction which resounds
0	yet dreadful in mine ear though in my choice
0	not to incur but soon his clear aspect
0	returned and gracious purpose thus renewed 
0	 not only these fair bounds but all the earth
0	to thee and to thy race i give as lords
0	possess it and all things that therein live 
0	or live in sea or air beast fish and fowl 
0	in sign whereof each bird and beast behold
