0	glanced on the ground with labour i must earn
0	my bread what harm idleness had been worse 
0	my labour will sustain me and lest cold
0	or heat should injure us his timely care
0	hath unbesought provided and his hands
0	clothed us unworthy pitying while he judged 
0	how much more if we pray him will his ear
0	be open and his heart to pity incline 
0	and teach us further by what means to shun
0	the inclement seasons rain ice hail and snow 
0	which now the sky with various face begins
0	to show us in this mountain while the winds
0	blow moist and keen shattering the graceful locks
0	of these fair spreading trees which bids us seek
0	some better shroud some better warmth to cherish
0	our limbs benummed ere this diurnal star
0	leave cold the night how we his gathered beams
0	reflected may with matter sere foment 
0	or by collision of two bodies grind
0	the air attrite to fire as late the clouds
0	justling or pushed with winds rude in their shock 
0	tine the slant lightning whose thwart flame driven down
0	kindles the gummy bark of fir or pine 
0	and sends a comfortable heat from far 
0	which might supply the sun such fire to use 
0	and what may else be remedy or cure
0	to evils which our own misdeeds have wrought 
0	he will instruct us praying and of grace
0	beseeching him so as we need not fear
0	to pass commodiously this life sustained
0	by him with many comforts till we end
0	in dust our final rest and native home 
0	what better can we do than to the place
0	repairing where he judged us prostrate fall
